### **推荐信草稿（英文版）**

To Whom It May Concern,

I am pleased to write this letter of recommendation in support of **Wenbin Hu**’s application for the **National Interest Waiver (NIW)**. As an academic and researcher specializing in **epileptic seizure prediction** and **neuroengineering**, I have had the privilege of closely following Hu’s impressive work, which I believe holds significant promise for advancing both **biomedical technologies** and **predictive healthcare systems**. Based on his substantial contributions to the field and the far-reaching implications of his research, I am confident that Hu’s work aligns with U.S. national interests and warrants consideration for the NIW.

Hu’s research represents a critical advancement in the area of **epileptic seizure prediction**, which remains a major challenge in both clinical and technological domains. His innovative approach to classifying **seizure phases**, specifically through the fine-grained categorization of **preictal** and **interictal periods**, has contributed to overcoming key barriers in **real-time seizure detection**. Traditionally, most predictive models have focused primarily on the **ictal** phase (the seizure event itself). However, Hu’s work introduced a novel approach by distinguishing multiple phases of the **preictal** period, allowing for **earlier and more accurate predictions**. This not only addresses critical gaps in **patient safety** but also promises to **improve clinical outcomes** by facilitating more timely interventions.

At the core of Hu’s research is the integration of **advanced machine learning techniques** with **neurophysiological signal processing**. By leveraging **deep learning algorithms**, particularly **Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs)**, Hu has developed models capable of automatically extracting high-dimensional features from raw EEG signals, thereby **eliminating manual preprocessing steps** and improving both efficiency and accuracy. This technical innovation significantly enhances the performance of seizure prediction systems, which are essential for minimizing healthcare costs and optimizing patient care.

Hu’s research has already had a measurable impact in the academic community, with his work being widely cited as a benchmark for the latest advancements in **seizure prediction models**. His models have set new standards in the field by demonstrating higher prediction accuracy and greater reliability compared to traditional methods. This work, in particular, has proven essential to the development of next-generation **neurological monitoring devices** and **predictive diagnostic tools**, which will undoubtedly shape the future of both clinical practice and **personalized medicine**.

The implications of Hu’s research extend well beyond epilepsy. The techniques he has developed for classifying EEG signals can be applied to a variety of neurological disorders, including **stroke**, **heart disease**, and **neurodegenerative conditions**. As the U.S. seeks to address the growing burden of chronic neurological diseases, Hu’s work is poised to play a key role in shaping the future of **predictive healthcare**. By improving the accuracy of **early diagnosis** and **real-time monitoring**, his contributions will directly align with U.S. efforts to reduce the economic burden of healthcare and improve the overall quality of life for patients with neurological conditions.

Hu’s contributions to the field are already recognized as groundbreaking, and his future research promises to lead to further innovations in **predictive diagnostics**. I am confident that his work will continue to have a transformative impact on **biomedical technologies**, providing critical solutions to the challenges of **patient care** and **public health** in the United States.

For these reasons, I strongly endorse **Wenbin Hu** for the **National Interest Waiver**. His innovative contributions to **seizure prediction** and **neurotechnology** demonstrate his potential to make lasting contributions to U.S. healthcare and biomedical research, and I am confident that his continued work will support the advancement of **predictive healthcare** technologies, improving both clinical outcomes and public health.

Please do not hesitate to contact me should you require further information or clarification.

Sincerely,  
[Your Full Name]  
[Your Position]  
[Your Institution]  
[Your Contact Information]

